So 02 April 2017

Tourists in Baden-Württemberg

Posted by Siwei Yang in python   

I 'm living in Baden-Württemberg, which is one of German Federal Lands. During my vacations I always see flood of holidaymakers. So I was just wondering, how many tourists are visiting this land. One day I occasionally ran into some interesting statistics about the tourists in this land, this information are provided by its official statistical agency . Specifically, there are annual statistical data about foreign tourists who came from 10 different countries and have visited Baden-Württemberg since 1960. Actually the data can be treated as several time series.

So let 's take a look, what the data can tell us. In this post I 'm focusing on the number of tourists as well as the number of overnight. I will first visualization of the trends of the given time series, then conduct some basic time series analysis. At the end of this post I will try to forecast the average number of overnight for French tourist in next 4 years.

1) Data reading and preoprocessing¶

Because the data originally was published in a complex html table, I just copied and pasted the data to several csv files and did some simple preprocessing. I think this will save time, otherwise I would have to parse html files in order to dredge the usefull data from them.

def convert2Int(df, rangecolumn):
    for col in df.columns[rangecolumn]:
        df[col] = [ int(x.replace('.', '')) for x in df[col].values]


def ReadFileAndPreproc(filename, rangecolumn, trunc = 0):
    df = pd.read_csv(filename, delimiter='\t',decimal = ',')
    convert2Int(df, rangecolumn)
    if trunc != 0:
        df = df.ix[trunc:]# because there is no data about Japan from 1960 to 1964, in this post I only used the data since 1965 for all countries 
    df.avg_stay = df.Overnight.values / df.Arrive.values # Due to the provided rounding  precision is not well preserved.  so we have to reconstruct the avg_stay
    df.set_index('Year', inplace = True)
    return df


austria = ReadFileAndPreproc("austria.csv", range(1,3) , trunc = 5)
belgien = ReadFileAndPreproc("belgien.csv", range(1,3), trunc= 5)
france = ReadFileAndPreproc("france.csv", range(1,3), trunc= 5)
italy = ReadFileAndPreproc("italy.csv", range(1,3), trunc= 5)
japan = ReadFileAndPreproc("japan.csv", range(1,3)) # Japan doesn't have data from 1960 to 1964
netherland = ReadFileAndPreproc("netherland.csv", range(1,3), trunc= 5)
sweden = ReadFileAndPreproc("sweden.csv", range(1,3), trunc= 5)
switzerland = ReadFileAndPreproc("switzerland.csv", range(1,3), trunc= 5)
uk = ReadFileAndPreproc("uk.csv", range(1,3), trunc= 5)
usa = ReadFileAndPreproc("usa.csv", range(1,3), trunc= 5)

3) Time Series Analysis¶

Obviously the data is a couple of time series. Such being the case, let us do some basic Time Series Analysis(TSA). At first I merge all data into one single dataframe in order to process data more conveniently later.

In [5]:
import seaborn as sns
import functools
def addprefixtoColumnName(df , prefix, inplace =False) :
    return df.rename_axis(lambda x: prefix + str(x), axis = 'columns', inplace = inplace)

for  n, l in zip(nationslist, label):
    addprefixtoColumnName(n, l+'_', inplace = True)

def join(x,y):
    return x.merge(y, left_index = True, right_index = True)

df_all = functools.reduce(join, nationslist)

Also a heatmap makes the correlation matrix more demonstrative. In this heatmap, red represents a positive correlation, while blue stands for negative correlation.

In [7]:
# Set up the matplotlib figure
f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(9, 7));

Whow! it seems that the tourists of some countries have correlated behaviour in term of overnight. For example Uk and Belgium, the corresponding correlation coefficient is 0.772711, meaning that if a English would like have more overnights in Baden-Württemberg, then a Belgian will also want stay longer in this state. It is a very interesting phenomenon. However this seems to be unaccountability. If you look at Japan and Italy, they also have a high correlation 0.713669. But these two countries are almost ten thousands of kilometers apart, and even have two totally different languages and cultures. Reader of this post may ask a question: How do they have such kind of tacit agreement?

Note that correlation is not causation, meaning that just because two things appear to be related to each other doesn’t mean that one causes the other. Furthermore, the correlation what we have could be a so-called spurious correlation, which is common problem especially for time series analysis. In exploring relationships between two time series, we should never directly observe this correlation in the first place, indstead we have to remove trend of the data at first. Actually there are already different approaches to deal with this. Now I am going to use a simple and non-parametric method to analyse the relationship between two countries again. It is called first difference. Using first difference we can easily remove the effect of trend. For details about this problem we refer to the post of Tom Fawcett.

The following code is a simple first difference.

In [8]:
f2, ax2 = plt.subplots(figsize=(9, 7));
df_diff = df_cor.diff();
corr_diff = df_diff.corr()
sns.heatmap(corr_diff, cmap=cmap, vmax=.9, square=True,  linewidths=.5, cbar_kws={"shrink": .5}, ax=ax2)
plt.xticks(rotation=40);
plt.yticks(rotation=40);

After differencing, we create the heatmap once again. Now the correlation between each pair of countries becomes much weaker than before, which seems to be more reasonable. So be carefull, when you want to use correlation for time series.

3.b) Modeling of Time Series¶

There are standard approaches for modeling of time series. In this article I tried to use the standard techinque to recover some structures from these time series.

Below I will build autocorrelation function(ACF) and partial autocorrelation function(PACF) as well as QQ-plot and probability-plot of our datasets. It turned out that all results are similar , so I think, that it is not necessary to list all counties here. Hence I selected three of them as representative examples. My implemantion was inspired by this great work.

import scipy.stats as scs
def tsplot(y, lags=None, figsize=(10, 8), style='bmh'):
    if not isinstance(y, pd.Series):
        y = pd.Series(y)
    with plt.style.context(style):    
        fig = plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
        layout = (3, 2)
        ts_ax = plt.subplot2grid(layout, (0, 0), colspan=2)
        acf_ax = plt.subplot2grid(layout, (1, 0))
        pacf_ax = plt.subplot2grid(layout, (1, 1))
        qq_ax = plt.subplot2grid(layout, (2, 0))
        pp_ax = plt.subplot2grid(layout, (2, 1))
        
        y.plot(ax=ts_ax)
        ts_ax.set_title('Time Series Analysis Plots')
        smt.graphics.plot_acf(y, lags=lags, ax=acf_ax, alpha=0.05)
        smt.graphics.plot_pacf(y, lags=lags, ax=pacf_ax, alpha=0.05)
        sm.qqplot(y, line='s', ax=qq_ax)
        qq_ax.set_title('QQ Plot')        
        scs.probplot(y, sparams=(y.mean(), y.std()), plot=pp_ax)

        plt.tight_layout()
    return

Looking at the three examples above, we notice that the partitial autocorrelation(PACF) indicates that an autoregressive(AR) model could be an apropriate model, because it shows a significant cutoff at lag 1. On the other hand, the autocorrelation(ACF) does not exhibit a significant cutoff like the case in PACF, so a pure moving average model may not be a good model. For this reason I first used AR model to describe all countries. Additinally using method select_order we can get the best lag order for an AR model.

In [14]:
maxlag = 50
reslist = []
for d in df_cor.columns:
    #print(d)
    mdl = smt.AR(df_cor[d].values).fit(maxlag=maxlag , ic='aic', trend='nc')
    est_order = smt.AR(df_cor[d].values).select_order( maxlag=maxlag, ic='aic', trend='nc')
    reslist.append((d, mdl, est_order))

for i in reslist:
    print('\n country : {}, coef estimate: {:3.4f} {:3.4f} | best lag order = {}'.format(i[0],  i[1].params[0],i[1].params[1], i[2]))

As expected, 1 is the best lag order for most of countries. Comparing other countries, we note that AR model might not be appropriate for France , because the best lag order is 29, which means too many parameters in the model. So let us try to create a new model for France using a little bit more complex approach called ARIMA. The following programm tries to figure out the best order configuration for ARIMA model.

In [16]:
best_aic = np.inf 
best_order = None
best_mdl = None

pq_rng = range(5) # [0,1,2,3,4]
d_rng = range(2) # [0,1]
for i in pq_rng:
    for d in d_rng:
        for j in pq_rng:
            try:
                #print('{} ,{}, {}]'.format(i,d, j))
                tmp_mdl = smt.ARIMA(df_cor.France.values, order=(i,d,j)).fit(method='mle', trend='nc')
                tmp_aic = tmp_mdl.aic
                if tmp_aic < best_aic:
                    best_aic = tmp_aic
                    best_order = (i, d, j)
                    best_mdl = tmp_mdl
            except: continue


print('aic: {:6.5f} | best order: {}'.format(best_aic, best_order))

aic: -140.08005 | best order: (3, 1, 2)

The best model here is q = 3, d = 1 , p = 2, which have much less parameters than the AR model created before. In order to assess a model, we may want to know if the residual or error of this model is a stationary process or some kind of white noise. It means that the residuals should be NOT autocorrelated. Furthermore the residuals should be normal distributed. If you are looking at the ACF or PACF, there should not be any significant non-0 lags, and the points in QQ-Plot should be lie on the line y = x. Finally we see, that it is the case for France. So at least we can say that the model is not bad.

The last task is forecasting. Using the ARIMA Model, we want to forecast the number of overnight the French tourist in next 4 years.

In [19]:
from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import ccf
n_steps = 5

f, err95, ci95 = best_mdl.forecast(steps=n_steps) # 95% CI
_, err99, ci99 = best_mdl.forecast(steps=n_steps, alpha=0.01) # 99% CI

idx = pd.date_range(str(df_cor.index[-1]), periods=n_steps, freq='A')
fc_95 = pd.DataFrame(np.column_stack([f, ci95]), 
                     index=idx, columns=['forecast', 'lower_ci_95', 'upper_ci_95'])
fc_99 = pd.DataFrame(np.column_stack([ci99]), 
                     index=idx, columns=['lower_ci_99', 'upper_ci_99'])
fc_all = fc_95.combine_first(fc_99)
fc_all.head(15)

Conclusion¶

In this post we have used visualization to see different trends of average number of overnight of foreign tourists, who come from 10 countries and have been visited Baden-Württemberg. Secondly we evaluated the correlation between each pair of countries, and then used basic approaches of Time Series Analysis to create model, and were able to forecast the average number of overnight for Frence tourists in the next 4 years.We will see.
